description:
R132H IDH1 is an &nbsp;important therapeutic target for a variety of brain cancers, yet drug leads and radiotracers which selectively bind only to the mutant over the wild type are so far lacking. &nbsp;Here we have predicted the structural determinants of the Michaelis complex of this mutant using a QM/MM MD-based protocol. It shows some important differences with the X-ray structure, from the metal coordination to the positioning of key residues at the active site. &nbsp;In particular, &nbsp;one lysine residue (K212) emerges as a mostly likely proton donor in the R132H IDH1 catalytic reaction. &nbsp;Intriguingly, the same residue &nbsp;in its deprotonated state &nbsp;is likely to be involved in the reaction catalyzed by the wild-type enzyme (though the mechanisms are different). &nbsp;Our QM/MM protocol could also be used for other metal-based enzymes, &nbsp;which cannot be modelled easily by force field-based MD, like in this case.&nbsp; 
 &nbsp; 
 The attached .zip file contains the following: 

  Coordinates : GROMACS coordinates and trajectory from the QM/MM simulation.

  Initial : The solvated crystal structure (with hydrogens and counterions) used to start the simulation (.gro format). Both, KH/D and K/DH protomer are given. 
  Final : The coordinates after 20 ps of MiMiC QM/MM MD from the step 3 of the protocol (.gro format). Both, KH/D and K/DH protomer are given. Furthermore for each protomer, each subunit (A and B) was seperately treated in the QM region. This results in 4 coordinate files. 
  Trajectory : The 20 ps MiMiC QM/MM MD trajectory from the step 3 of the protocol (.xtc format). This is sampled at every 0.25 ps with a dt of 0.0005 ps. Both, KH/D and K/DH protomer are given. Furthermore for each protomer, each subunit (A and B) was seperately treated in the QM region. This results in 4 trajectory files. 





  Protocol : Input files and recipe used to run the QM/MM MD simulations of mut-IDH1. 
  Topology : GROMACS topology used for each protomer. 


 &nbsp;

